{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515950","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515950"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:36:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:36:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12537"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12537","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12537"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.35,0.11,0.22,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5036"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101622"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5036","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5036"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12537"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84064"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2702"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8358"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8376"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17631"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17915"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18235"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18397"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33048"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33103"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34686"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46426"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101622","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101622"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of worsening fever, a non-productive cough, a runny nose, and shortness of breath. His difficulty in breathing is mildly worsened on lying down. He migrated to Australia from India three months ago. His medical history consists of asthma and hypertension. His regular medications are salbutamol PRN and perindopril.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his blood pressure is 132/84 mmHg, pulse rate 82/min, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 95% on room air, and temperature 38.3\u00b0C. His cardiorespiratory examination reveals dual heart sounds with no murmurs, non-elevated jugular venous pressure, and bibasal crepitations. No pedal oedema is evident. An ABG is collected:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH 7.32 (7.35-7.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpCO2 48 mmHg (35-45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpO2 80 mmHg (80-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHCO3 24 mmol/L (22-26)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EsO2 95% (95-98%)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 135 g/L (130-170)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 12 x10\u2079/L (4-11)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeutrophils 8.4 x10\u2079/L (2.0-7.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELymphocytes 2.4 x10\u2079/L (1.0-4.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMonocytes 1.2 x10\u2079/L (0.2-1.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEosinophils 0.0 x10\u2079/L (0.0-0.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBasophils 0.0 x10\u2079/L (0.0-0.1)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 250 x10\u2079/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC-reactive protein 50 mg/L (\u0026lt;5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChest X-ray: diffuse bilateral interstitial infiltrates with a reticular pattern and no focal consolidation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bacterial pneumonia","Viral pneumonia","Fungal pneumonia","Tuberculosis","Acute pericarditis with heart failure"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGradually worsening symptoms with upper respiratory tract symptoms such as rhinorrhoea, together with chest X-ray findings of diffuse bilateral interstitial infiltrates and bloods showing a mildly elevated white blood cell count are suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Eviral pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOf note the blood test results show a mildly elevated white cell count with mildly raised neutrophils and monocytes and lymphocytes in the normal range. While lymphocytosis is classically associated with viral infections, it\u0027s important to note that viral pneumonia can also present with normal lymphocyte counts or even lymphopenia in some cases. The mildly elevated neutrophil count seen here is also common in viral pneumonia, with severely elevated white cell counts and neutrophilia more characteristic of bacterial pneumonia. The arterial blood gas shows a mild respiratory acidosis, consistent with impaired gas exchange due to pneumonia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E would likely present with chest X-ray findings including alveolar infiltrates, lobar consolidation, and pleural effusion. While this patient does have a mildly elevated neutrophil count, bacterial pneumonia typically presents with a more significantly elevated white cell count and neutrophilia (often \u0026gt;15 x10\u2079/L). The presence of upper respiratory symptoms and diffuse bilateral interstitial infiltrates without focal consolidation is more consistent with viral aetiology. Chest X-ray is a useful tool in differentiating viral from bacterial pneumonia, with viral pneumonia typically showing diffuse, bilateral interstitial patterns, while bacterial pneumonia more commonly presents with focal consolidation in a lobar or segmental distribution.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFungal pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with a more gradual onset of symptoms and different chest X-ray findings. Fungal infections include \u003Cem\u003EAspergillus\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003ECryptococcus\u003C/em\u003E and are more common in immunocompromised patients. The blood picture would also be different, often with eosinophilia in some fungal infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETuberculosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a more chronic course, often with constitutional symptoms such as weight loss, night sweats, and a productive cough. Chest X-ray findings in tuberculosis often include upper lobe infiltrates, cavitation, or nodular opacities, rather than the diffuse bilateral interstitial infiltrates seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute pericarditis with heart failure\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely given the lack of chest pain and lack of other signs and symptoms of heart failure such as paroxysmal nocturnal dyspnoea, nocturia, non-elevated JVP, and peripheral oedema. The chest X-ray would typically show cardiomegaly and pulmonary vascular congestion rather than infiltrates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditional investigations that can help differentiate viral from bacterial pneumonia include viral polymerase chain reaction (PCR) testing, which can identify specific viral pathogens from respiratory specimens. Bacterial cultures of sputum or blood can identify bacterial pathogens, though these may take several days to yield results. Procalcitonin is a biomarker that can be particularly useful in differentiating bacterial from viral infections, with levels typically elevated (\u0026gt;0.5 ng/mL) in bacterial infections but remaining low in viral infections. These investigations, combined with clinical presentation and initial laboratory findings, can guide appropriate antimicrobial therapy and avoid unnecessary antibiotic use in viral pneumonia cases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Viral pneumonia often presents with bilateral lung infiltrates and upper respiratory symptoms.","Raised lymphocytes and monocytes in patients with pneumonia suggest a viral aetiology, though lymphopenia can also occur.","Arterial blood gas interpretation is essential in respiratory infections to assess gas exchange and acid-base status."],"references":["Freeman AM, Leigh, Jr TR. Viral Pneumonia. In: StatPearls [online]. [Updated 2022 Jul 4]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK513286/","Iqbal MA, Gupta M. Cardiogenic Pulmonary Edema. In: StatPearls [online]. [Updated 2022 Jun 27]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK544260/","Ruuskanen O, Lahti E, Jennings LC, Murdoch DR. Viral pneumonia. Lancet. 2011 Apr 9;377(9773):1264-75. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7138033/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84064"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12537"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84064","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84064"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-03T14:42:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-0